# =============================================================================

# .dockerignore — Files excluded from the Docker build context

# =============================================================================

#

# WHAT THIS FILE DOES:

# When you run `docker build`, Docker sends ALL files in the build context

# directory to the Docker daemon. This file works like .gitignore — it

# prevents unnecessary files from being sent, which:

# 1. Speeds up the build (less data to transfer)

# 2. Prevents accidentally including secrets or large files in the image

# 3. Improves cache efficiency (irrelevant file changes won't bust cache)

#

# =============================================================================

# --- Version control ---

# The .git directory can be huge and is never needed inside a container.

.git/
.gitignore
.gitattributes

# --- Build outputs ---

# These are compiled locally and will be rebuilt inside the container.

# Including them would waste space and could cause architecture mismatches

# (e.g., building on macOS ARM but running on Linux x86).

**/bin/
**/obj/

# --- IDE and editor files ---

# Editor configs, workspace settings, and debug configs are developer-specific.

.vs/
.vscode/
.idea/
_.user
_.suo

# --- OS files ---

.DS_Store
Thumbs.db

# --- Environment and secrets ---

# NEVER include .env files in Docker images — they contain credentials.

# Only .env.example (which has placeholder values) is safe.

.env
.env.\*
!.env.example

# --- Docker files ---

# Prevents circular inclusion and keeps the context clean.

\*_/Dockerfile_
.dockerignore
docker-compose*.yml
compose*.yaml

# --- Documentation ---

# Not needed at build time.

README.md
CHANGELOG.md
LICENSE
docs/

# --- Database init scripts ---

# These are for docker-compose volume mounts, not for the API image.

db/
